Imposing restrictions on childcare accounts
	If such conditions as may be specified in regulations are met, HMRC maymake an account restriction order.
	An “account restriction order” is an order imposing any of the followingrestrictions in relation to a childcare account specified in the order—
		a restriction that prevents the making of any qualifying payments into thechildcare account;
		a restriction that prevents the making of any payments from the childcareaccount in respect of qualifying childcare.
	Regulations may, in particular, provide that HMRC may make an accountrestriction order where—
		a person wishes—
		to open a childcare account in respect of a child, or
		to make a declaration of eligibility in relation to a childcare accountheld in respect of a child, and
		another person holds a childcare account in respect of the child.
	Regulations may make further provision about account restriction orders,including, in particular—
		provision about the procedure for making an account restriction order;
		provision enabling an account restriction order to impose a restriction fora period specified in the order (which may be unlimited);
		provision enabling an account restriction order to provide that arestriction does not apply in such cases as may be specified in the order;
		provision enabling a person who wishes to open a childcare account or makea declaration of eligibility to apply to HMRC for an account restriction orderto be made in relation to another person who holds a childcare account;
		provision enabling an account restriction order to be revoked, includingprovision for the account-holder to apply for its revocation;
		provision specifying the circumstances in which such an application may begranted.
	If an account restriction order is made in relation to a childcare account—
		HMRC must give a copy of the order to the account-holder and to the accountprovider, and
		the account provider must comply with the order.

Final provisions
	Regulations: general
		Any power to make regulations under this Act is exercisable by statutoryinstrument.
		Any power to make regulations under the following provisions of this Act isexercisable by the Treasury—
			section 1(5) (power to amend rate of top-up payment);
			section 2(3)(b) to (d) (qualifying childcare);
			sections 3, 7 to 11 and 13 (eligibility);
			section 5(2) (power to alter length of entitlement period);
			section 14 (qualifying child);
			section 19(7) (power to amend the relevant maximum);
			section 30 (termination of tax credit awards);
			section 31 (power to provide for automatic termination of universalcredit);
			sections 32 and 33 (disqualification of tax credit or universal creditclaimants from obtaining top-up payments);
			sections 43(5), 44(6) and 46(5) (powers to vary certain penalties);
			section 50(4) (power to alter period for which directions under section 50have effect);
			section 62(6) (power to amend rate of compensatory payments);
			section 72 (power to make consequential amendments);
			section 75 (commencement).
		Any power to make regulations under a provision of this Act that is notmentioned in subsection (2) is exercisable by the Commissioners for HerMajesty’s Revenue and Customs.
		Regulations under this Act may—
			make different provision for different purposes or in relation to differentareas,
			contain incidental, supplemental, consequential or transitional provisionor savings, and
			provide for a person to exercise a discretion in dealing with any matter.
		Subsection (4) does not apply to regulations under section 75 (see insteadsubsection (3) of that section).
	Regulations: Parliamentary control
		A statutory instrument containing regulations under this Act is subject toannulment in pursuance of a resolution of either House of Parliament, unlessthe instrument—
			is required by subsection (3) or any other enactment to be laid in draftbefore, and approved by a resolution of, each House, or
			contains only regulations under section 75.
		Subsection (3) applies to a statutory instrument that contains (with orwithout other provisions)—
			regulations under section 1(5);
			regulations under section 2(3)(b), (c) or (d);
			the first regulations under each of sections 3 and 7 to 10;
			regulations under section 5(2);
			the first regulations under section 14;
			regulations under section 19(7) which substitute a lower amount for anyamount for the time being specified in section 19(5);
			regulations under section 31;
			the first regulations under each of sections 32(5) and 33(5);
			regulations under section 32(6) or 33(6);
			regulations under section 43(5), 44(6) or 46(5);
			regulations under section 50(4);
			regulations under section 62(6);
			regulations under section 72.
		A statutory instrument to which this subsection applies may not be madeunless a draft of the instrument has been laid before, and approved by aresolution of, each House of Parliament.
	Interpretation 
		In this Act—
			  * “account-holder” has the meaning given by section 15(10); 
			  * “account provider” has the meaning given by section 15(10); 
			  * “appealable decision” has the meaning given by section 56(3); 
			  * “childcare” has the meaning given by section 2(1); 
			  * “childcare account” has the meaning given by section 15; 
			  * “the Commissioners” means the Commissioners for Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs; 
			  * “declaration of eligibility” has the meaning given by section 4; 
			  * “enactment” includes— 
			an enactment contained in subordinate legislation,
			an enactment contained in, or in an instrument made under, an Act of theScottish Parliament,
			an enactment contained in, or in an instrument made under, a Measure or Act ofthe National Assembly for Wales, and
			an enactment contained in, or in an instrument made under, Northern Irelandlegislation;
				  * “entitlement period” means a period determined in accordance with section 5; 
				  * “HMRC” means Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs; 
				  * “ITEPA 2003” means the Income Tax (Earnings and Pensions) Act 2003; 
				  * “partner” is to be read in accordance with regulations made under section 3(5); 
				  * “permitted payment” has the meaning given by section 20(3); 
				  * “prohibited payment” has the meaning given by section 20(4); 
				  * “qualifying child” has the meaning given by section 14; 
				  * “qualifying childcare” has the meaning given by section 2(2); 
				  * “qualifying payment” has the meaning given by section 19; 
				  * “tax credit” has the same meaning as in the Tax Credits Act 2002; 
				  * “top-up element”, in relation to an amount, has the meaning given by section 21; 
				  * “top-up payment” is to be read in accordance with section 1; 
				  * “universal credit” means universal credit payable under— 
			Part 1 of the Welfare Reform Act 2012, or
			any provision made for Northern Ireland which corresponds to that Part of thatAct.
		In this Act—
			references to a valid declaration of eligibility are to be read inaccordance with section 4(2), and
			references to an active childcare account are to be read in accordance withsection 17(3).
	Power to make consequential amendments
		Regulations may make such provision amending, repealing, revoking orapplying with modifications any enactment to which this section applies as theTreasury consider necessary or expedient in consequence of any provision madeby or under this Act.
		This section applies to—
			any enactment passed or made before the passing of this Act, and
			any enactment passed or made on or before the last day of the Session inwhich this Act is passed.
	Financial provisions
		There is to be paid out of money provided by Parliament any increaseattributable to this Act in the sums payable under any other Act out of moneyso provided.
		Subsections (3) and (4) apply if childcare accounts are provided by theCommissioners or the Director of Savings (“the relevant account provider”).
		Sums paid into childcare accounts are not to be paid into the ConsolidatedFund.
		Sums payable from childcare accounts are not to be regarded as expenditureof the relevant account provider.
	Extent 
		Except as provided by subsection (2), this Act extends to England andWales, Scotland and Northern Ireland.
		Any amendment or repeal made by this Act has the same extent as theprovision amended or repealed.
	Commencement and short title
		The following provisions of this Act come into force on the day on whichthis Act is passed—
			sections 65 and 68;
			sections 69 to 72, 73(1), 74 and this section;
			any power to make regulations under this Act.
		The remaining provisions of this Act come into force in accordance withprovision contained in regulations.
		Regulations under subsection (2) may—
			make different provision for different purposes or in relation to differentareas;
			make such transitory or transitional provision, or savings, as the Treasuryconsider necessary or expedient, including (in particular) such adaptations ofprovisions of this Act brought into force as appear to be necessary orexpedient in consequence of other provisions of this Act not yet having comeinto force.
		This Act may be cited as the Childcare Payments Act 2014.
